"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1105877","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-04-02","<p>Data on the number of recommended health visitor visits carried out in the United Kingdom are not available in the format requested.</p><p> </p><p>The health visitor service delivery metrics currently cover the antenatal contact, new birth visit, the six-eight week review, the 12-month review and the two-two and half year review and can be viewed at the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/child-and-maternal-health-statistics#health-visitor-service-delivery-metrics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/child-and-maternal-health-statistics#health-visitor-service-delivery-metrics</a></p><p> </p><p>The metrics do not indicate whether parents already have a child or are new parents.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","238393","2019-04-02T16:12:33.873Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1105877/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1105877/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1105877/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-03-28","Health Visitors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many and what proportion of eligible new parents received the recommended health visitor visits at (a) 28 weeks of pregnancy, (b) between ten days and two weeks after birth, (c) between six and eight weeks after birth, (d) between nine months and one year after birth and (e) between two years and two and a half years after birth, in each region of the UK, in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Anneliese Dodds","Oxford East","Anneliese Dodds","238392"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1105878","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-04-02","<p>Data on the number of recommended health visitor visits carried out in the United Kingdom are not available in the format requested.</p><p> </p><p>The health visitor service delivery metrics currently cover the antenatal contact, new birth visit, the six-eight week review, the 12-month review and the two-two and half year review and can be viewed at the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/child-and-maternal-health-statistics#health-visitor-service-delivery-metrics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/child-and-maternal-health-statistics#health-visitor-service-delivery-metrics</a></p><p> </p><p>The metrics do not indicate whether parents already have a child or are new parents.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","238392","2019-04-02T16:12:33.92Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1105878/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1105878/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1105878/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-03-28","Health Visitors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many and what proportion of eligible parents of a second or subsequent child received the recommended health visitor visits at (a) 28 weeks of pregnancy, (b) between ten days and two weeks after birth, (c) between six and eight weeks after birth, (d) between nine months and one year after birth and (e) between two years and two and a half years after birth, in each region of the UK, in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Anneliese Dodds","Oxford East","Anneliese Dodds","238393"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1105879","Department for Transport","false","2019-04-02","<p>I am aware that Nexus have identified several possible extensions to the Tyne and Wear Metro system. It would be up to Nexus to identify which of these would be the most effective and to develop a business case and seek funding accordingly.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is supporting the Tyne and Wear Metro system with £317 million for its reinvigoration and renewal programme and £229 million towards its running costs since 2010. Furthermore, in the 2017 Autumn Budget, the Chancellor announced a £337m direct grant to deliver a new fleet of trains for the Tyne and Wear Metro. Through the New Stations Fund the Department is also supporting the construction of a new station at Horden Peterlee on the Durham Coast Line in the Hon. Member’s constituency.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2019-04-02T12:23:01.16Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1105879/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1105879/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1105879/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-03-28","Railways: Easington","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will take steps to improve regional rail connectivity in the Easington constituency through funding the expansion of the Tyne and Wear Metro into East Durham.","false","Biography information for Grahame Morris","Easington","Grahame Morris","238325"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1105880","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-04-02","<p>As set out in the Written Statement of 20 June 2018, regulatory provisions, including relevant building regulations, are excluded are excluded from the Business Impact Target if certified by departments or regulators as relating to the safety of tenants, residents and occupants in buildings that stem from, or relate to, Government’s response to the Grenfell tragedy, reviews, inquiries or working groups.</p><p> </p>","Rochester and Strood","Kelly Tolhurst",,"2019-04-02T16:41:55.833Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1105880/answer","Biography information for Kelly Tolhurst","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1105880/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1105880/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-03-28","Buildings: Fire Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to Written Statement of 20 June 2018, on Business Impact Target, HCWS776, whether exclusion from the business impact target as set out in that statement applies to the (a) conduct of fire risk assessment and fire safety training across different housing types and business types, and (b) provision of appropriate fire-fighting equipment, fire safety signs, emergency lighting and fire alarm systems across different housing types and business types.","false","Biography information for Anneliese Dodds","Oxford East","Anneliese Dodds","238394"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1105881","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-04-02","<p>As set out in the Written Statement of 20 June 2018, regulatory provisions, including relevant building regulations, are excluded are excluded from the Business Impact Target if certified by departments or regulators as relating to the safety of tenants, residents and occupants in buildings that stem from, or relate to, Government’s response to the Grenfell tragedy, reviews, inquiries or working groups.</p>","Rochester and Strood","Kelly Tolhurst",,"2019-04-02T16:42:04.437Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1105881/answer","Biography information for Kelly Tolhurst","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1105881/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1105881/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-03-28","Building Regulations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Written Statement of 20 June 2018 on Business Impact Target, HCWS776, whether exclusion from the business impact target as set out in that Statement applies to all elements of the Building Regulations; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Anneliese Dodds","Oxford East","Anneliese Dodds","238395"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1105882","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2019-04-02","<p>Historically, the main source of non-public income generated for NCS has been the £50 sign-up fee. A small amount of income has occasionally come from other sources, such as corporate sponsorships.</p><p> </p><p>The forecasted circa £3 million income for the upcoming financial year will be generated from sign-up fees.</p>","Eastleigh","Mims Davies",,"2019-04-02T10:30:39.55Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1105882/answer","Biography information for Mims Davies","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1105882/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1105882/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2019-03-28","Voluntary Work: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, pursuant to the Answer of 26 March 2019 to Question 235376 on Voluntary Work: Young People, what the sources are of past non-public income generated to fund NCS and the forecasted £3 million of income for the upcoming financial year.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","238396"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1105883","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-04-04","<p>The consultation on allergen information provisions, which closed on Friday 29 March, was a joint UK wide consultation between Defra, the Foods Standards Agency in England, Northern Ireland and Wales, and Food Standards Scotland. As food labelling is a devolved issue, the decision to run the consultation across the whole of the United Kingdom was dependent upon the support and involvement of the devolved administrations. Throughout the process, Defra officials have been working closely with officials from Food Standards Scotland and the Food Standards Agency.</p><p> </p><p>Looking to the future, we will continue to work closely with the devolved administrations to ensure that all UK consumers have complete trust in the food they consume.</p>","Macclesfield","David Rutley",,"2019-04-04T15:36:39.143Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1105883/answer","Biography information for David Rutley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1105883/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1105883/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-03-28","Food: Labelling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what discussions his Department has had with devolved Administrations on the consultation on proposed amendments to the domestic Food Information Regulations 2014 (FIR) (England) and parallel FIR regulations in Northern Ireland, Scotland and Wales relating to allergen information for foods that are prepacked for direct sale to the consumer on the same premises from which they are sold.","false","Biography information for Kirstene Hair","Angus","Kirstene Hair","238397"
